<SiteLayout site="westmount" title="SCHD Dividend Analysis & History" description="Discover the long-term historical dividend performance of the Schwab U.S. Dividend Equity ETF. What does its trajectory look like for the upcoming year?" canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/schd-dividend" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>SCHD Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A Deep Dive into Yield, Growth, and Payout Stability</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <p>When investors seek out robust, reliable equity income, the Schwab U.S. Dividend Equity ETF (SCHD) invariably enters the conversation. As a cornerstone for many dividend growth portfolios, SCHD is designed to track the total return of the Dow Jones U.S. Dividend 100 Index. This focus ensures the fund is heavily weighted towards fundamentally sound companies with established track records of consistently paying—and growing—their dividends. In this comprehensive guide, we unpack the SCHD dividend profile, exploring its current yield, payout frequency, historical performance, and how it measures up against category averages.</p>

      <h2>Current Dividend Yield & Payout Details</h2>
      <p>Understanding the immediate income potential of any dividend ETF begins with its current yield. The yield represents the annual dividend income relative to the ETF's current share price. While market fluctuations cause this figure to move daily, SCHD is well-regarded for maintaining a yield that frequently outpaces the broader S&P 500 average, typically resting in the neighborhood of 3% to 4%.</p>

      <p>The <strong>schd dividend payout</strong> is structured on a quarterly schedule. This predictable cash flow is a major draw for retirees and income-focused investors who rely on regular distributions to cover living expenses or to fuel a dividend reinvestment plan (DRIP). The crucial dates for investors to monitor are the ex-dividend dates, which generally fall in the latter half of March, June, September, and December. To capture the quarterly distribution, an investor must be a shareholder of record prior to the ex-dividend date.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Key SCHD Metrics</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Fund Inception:</strong> October 2011</li>
          <li><strong>Expense Ratio:</strong> 0.06%</li>
          <li><strong>Payout Frequency:</strong> Quarterly</li>
          <li><strong>Typical Ex-Dividend Months:</strong> March, June, September, December</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Historical Dividend Performance (5-Year Lookback)</h2>
      <p>The true power of SCHD lies not just in its starting yield, but in its ability to grow that payout over time. The ETF's methodology naturally selects companies with a history of at least 10 consecutive years of dividend payments. This stringent criterion translates into a robust <strong>schd dividend history</strong> at the fund level. Let's examine the actual quarterly payouts from recent years to observe the trajectory of cash returned to shareholders.</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Ex-Dividend Date</th>
            <th>Amount (USD)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Dec 2024</td><td>$0.265</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sep 2024</td><td>$0.252</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Jun 2024</td><td>$0.275</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Mar 2024</td><td>$0.204</td></tr>
